# No em or en dashes in public-facing copy

**Hard rule for user-visible text:** never use em dashes (U+2014) or en dashes (U+2013) in public-facing copy. Use a normal ASCII hyphen (`-`), or restructure with a comma, colon, period, or parentheses.

## Where this applies

- HTML / document `<title>` and page metadata (`title`, `openGraph.title`, etc.)
- Visible headings, hero text, buttons, modals, footer copy
- Any string rendered to end users on the site
- README.md and docs/ Markdown prose

## Allowed

- Hyphen-minus `-` as a separator: `Adult Addons - Stremio & Nuvio`
- Attributive compound hyphens: `18+ only`, `4K-ready` (when the compound is standard)
- Hyphens inside code identifiers, URLs, flags, and CLI args

## Not allowed

- `—` (U+2014 em dash)
- `–` (U+2013 en dash)
- Spaced double hyphen used as a dash: ` -- `

## With humanizer

Run **humanizer** on substantive UI copy. This rule is the non-negotiable dash constraint; humanizer covers the wider de-AI patterns. Before shipping public-facing text, scan for `—` and `–` and fix any hits.

## Quick check

```bash
rg '[—–]' README.md docs/
```
